            <para>
                <title>OWNER NOTIFICATION</title>
            </para>
            <para>Navistar will notify owners of this campaign on their vehicles. A listing of owner names and addresses
                has been furnished to the involved dealers to enable dealers to follow up with owners to have the
                vehicles corrected. You must limit the use of this listing to this campaign since the list may contain
                information obtained from state motor vehicle registration records and the use of such motor vehicle
                registration data for purposes other than this campaign is a violation of law in several states.
            </para>
        </defect>
        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="2">
            <title>REPAIR PROCEDURES</title>
            <svcprocinfo>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">Before performing the service, please read and understand the following
                        instructions completely.
                    </emph>
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>To prevent serious eye injury, always wear safe eye protection when you perform vehicle
                            maintenance or service.
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>Block the wheels to prevent the vehicle from moving. Support the vehicle with safety
                            stands. Do not work under a vehicle supported only by jacks. Jacks can slip or fall over
                            resulting in serious personal injury or death.
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">FROM THE ABOVE "MODELS INVOLVED" SECTION OF THIS LETTER USE THE BUILD DATE OF THE
                        VEHICLE TO DETERMINE WHICH REPAIR GROUP PROCEDURE BELOW IS REQUIRED.
                    </emph>
                </para>
            </svcprocinfo>
            <svcsubproc>
                <title>REPAIR GROUP 1 PROCEDURE</title>
                <para>The vehicles in this Repair Group have hoses that are too long. Each vehicle in this Repair Group
                    will require a hose routing kit unless both of the hoses are replaced because of chafing damage (#
                    3538974C92). If only one hose is damaged from chafing, replace both hoses. If both hoses are
                    replaced, the hose routing kit is not needed.
                </para>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">Please read steps carefully before proceeding.</emph>
                </para>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Inspecting both drop hoses for chafing damage:</para>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">If both hoses
                            <emph type="bold">ARE NOT DAMAGED</emph>
                            from chafing, skip to step 2. Installing the hose routing kit (#8900069R91).
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">If one or both hoses are damaged from chafing, skip to step 3. Replacing the
                            drop hoses.
                            <emph type="bold">Kit #8900069R91 is not needed.</emph>
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Installing the hose routing kit #8900069R91:</para>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Remove the bolt on the right rear side of the axle housing. Remove the bolt on
                            the left rear side of the axle housing (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9950801">see Figure 1</hotlnk>). Save the bolts for step C.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Put the p-clamps around the hoses (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9950801">see Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Attach the p-clamps to the back of the axle housing using the removed bolts
                            (from step A.) and two lock washers from the kit #8900069R91 (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9950801">see Figure 1</hotlnk>). Do not tighten the bolts.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Position the extra hose length on both sides of the p-clamp to prevent the hoses
                            from contacting any axle or suspension components. Make sure there are no kinks in the
                            hoses.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Tighten the bolts to the axle housing.</para>
                    </step2>
                </step1>
                <figure id="f9950801" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g9950801.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"/>
                    <caption>Repair Group 1, P-Clamping Hoses to Back Side of Axle Housing, Left Side Shown, Right Side
                        Similar
                    </caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. P-CLAMP</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. BOLT AND LOCK WASHER</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Replacing the drop hoses:</para>
                    <specpara>
                        <caution>
                            <para>To avoid a lengthy bleeding procedure be sure the brake pedal is not accidentally
                                depressed after the brake hose fittings have been loosened.
                            </para>
                        </caution>
                    </specpara>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Unfasten the hose clamps at the caliper and top of the axle housing.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Cut off all the cable ties that connect the ABS wiring to the brake hose.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Prepare for fluid loss at the hose ends and remove the brake hose.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Attach the new hose to the steel tubing at the frame rail and then at the
                            caliper (torque end fittings to 9-14 ft-lbs).
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Attach and tighten the hose clamps at the top of the axle housing and at the
                            caliper.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Cable tie the ABS wiring to the hose at the three barrel isolators on the brake
                            hose.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Change the drop hose on the opposite side following steps A. through F and then
                            bleed the rear brake system (for ABS BLEEDING PROCEDURE, Ref. CTS-5274, 11.1., steps 1-8)
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Clean up spilled brake fluid.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Test the brake function and inspect for leakage at hoses and fittings.</para>
                    </step2>
                </step1>
            </svcsubproc>
            <svcsubproc>
                <title>REPAIR GROUP 2 PROCEDURE</title>
                <para>Each of the vehicles in this Repair Group will have both hoses replaced and will require two
                    replacement hoses
                    <emph type="bold">#3538974C92</emph>.
                </para>
                <para>
                    <title>Hose Replacement Instructions:</title>
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>To avoid a lengthy bleeding procedure be sure the brake pedal is not accidentally
                            depressed after the brake hose fittings have been loosened.
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
                <seqlist>
                    <item>
                        <para>Unfasten the hose clamps at the caliper and top of the axle housing.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Cut off all the cable ties that connect the ABS wiring to the brake hose.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Prepare for fluid loss at the hose ends and remove the brake hose.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Attach the new hose to the steel tubing at the frame rail and then at the caliper (torque
                            end fittings to 9-14 ft-lbs).
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Attach and tighten the hose clamps at the top of the axle housing and at the caliper.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Cable tie the ABS wiring to the hose at the three barrel isolators on the brake hose.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Change the drop hose on the opposite side following steps A. through F. and then bleed the
                            rear brake system (for ABS BLEEDING PROCEDURE, Ref. CTS-5274, 11.1., steps 1-8).
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Clean up spilled brake fluid.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Test the brake function and inspect for leakage at hoses and fittings.</para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
            </svcsubproc>
            <svcsubproc>
                <title>REPAIR GROUP 3 PROCEDURE</title>
                <para>The vehicles in this Repair Group have hoses that are too long and will require the installation
                    of a hose routing kit. Each vehicle will require one hose routing kit #8900070R91 unless the hoses
                    are replaced due to chafing damage. If only one hose is damaged from chafing, replace both hoses.
                </para>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Inspecting both drop hoses for chafing damage:</para>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">If both hoses
                            <emph type="bold">ARE NOT DAMAGED</emph>
                            from chafing, skip to step 2. Installing the hose routing kit (#8900070R91).
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">If one or both hoses are damaged from chafing, skip to step 3. Replacing the
                            drop hoses.
                            <emph type="bold">Kit #8900070R91 is not needed.</emph>
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                </step1>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Installing the hose routing kit #8900070R91:</para>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Install the stand-off brackets under the hose brackets mounted on top of the
                            axle housing (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9950802">see Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Put a p-clamp around each hose and attach the p-clamp to the stand-off brackets
                            (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f9950802">see Figure 2</hotlnk>). Be sure to mount the p-clamp on top of the
                            stand-off bracket with the bolt head on top and the threads pointed down. Do not tighten the
                            p-clamp bolts.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Position the extra hose length on both sides of the p-clamps to prevent the
                            hoses from contacting any axle or suspension components. Make sure there are no kinks in the
                            hoses.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Check for chafing points and tighten the p-clamp bolts.</para>
                    </step2>
                </step1>
                <figure id="f9950802" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g9950802.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"/>
                    <caption>Repair Group 3, Installing Stand-Off Bracket to Top of Axle Housing, Left Side Shown, Right
                        Side Similar
                    </caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. P-CLAMP ON TOP OF FLAT EXTENSION BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. NUT ON BOTTOM SIDE OF FLAT EXTENSION BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. STAND-OFF BRACKET UNDER HOSE BRACKET</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <step1>
                    <para count="1">Replacing the drop hoses:</para>
                    <specpara>
                        <caution>
                            <para>To avoid a lengthy bleeding procedure be sure the brake pedal is not accidentally
                                depressed after the brake hose fittings have been loosened.
                            </para>
                        </caution>
                    </specpara>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Unfasten the hose clamps at the caliper and top of the axle housing.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Cut off all the cable ties that connect the ABS wiring to the brake hose.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Prepare for fluid loss at the hose ends and remove the brake hose.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Attach the new hose to the steel tubing at the frame rail and then at the
                            caliper (torque end fittings to 9-14 ft-lbs).
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Attach and tighten the hose clamps at the top of the axle housing and at the
                            caliper.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Cable tie the ABS wiring to the hose at the three barrel isolators on the brake
                            hose.
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Change the drop hose on the opposite side, if necessary, following steps A.
                            through F and then bleed the rear brake system (for ABS BLEEDING PROCEDURE, Ref. CTS-5274,
                            11.1., steps 1-8)
                        </para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Clean up spilled brake fluid.</para>
                    </step2>
                    <step2>
                        <para count="1">Test the brake function and inspect for leakage at hoses and fittings.</para>
                    </step2>
                </step1>
            </svcsubproc>
        </svcproc>
